The development of synthetic biology and metabolic engineering provides opportunities for the microbial biosynthesis of monoterpenoids (
 Chandran et al., 2011). Industrial-scale production of some terpenoids using engineered microorganisms have been realized, such as artemisinin acid and ginsenosides (
 Paddon et al., 2013; 
 Yan et al., 2014; 
 Wang P. et al., 2015; 
 Wei et al., 2015; 
 Yang et al., 2020). Recovery of the monoterpenoid biosynthetic pathways and introduction of essential key enzymes into proper microbial host can lead to the production of targeted monoterpenoids (
 Zebec et al., 2016; 
 Ignea et al., 2019). These provide an alternative way to sustainably supply of monoterpenoids and other Chinese herb-derived natural product (
 Guan et al., 2020; 
 Wang et al., 2020).
